1
00:00:47,251 --> 00:00:49,276
Travel is useful,
it exercises the imagination.

2
00:00:49,306 --> 00:00:51,156
All the rest
is disappointment and fatigue.

3
00:00:51,186 --> 00:00:53,606
Our journey is entirely imaginary.
That is its strength.

4
00:00:53,636 --> 00:00:54,826
It goes from life to death.

5
00:00:54,856 --> 00:00:57,016
People, animals, cities, things,
all are imagined.

6
00:00:57,046 --> 00:00:58,852
It's a novel,
just a fictitious narrative.

7
00:00:58,882 --> 00:01:02,052
Littre says so, and he's never wrong.
And besides, anyone can do as much.

8
00:01:02,082 --> 00:01:04,902
You just have to close your eyes.
It's on the other side of life.

9
00:01:04,932 --> 00:01:07,201
Louis-Ferdinand Celine
Journey to the End of the Night

10
00:01:11,611 --> 00:01:13,044
Fire!

11
00:02:35,011 --> 00:02:36,763
You're a real pain in the ass!

12
00:04:37,571 --> 00:04:38,924
Enough!

13
00:04:39,051 --> 00:04:41,884
They even have cocktails
with cherries. Remember?

14
00:04:42,011 --> 00:04:44,366
Hey, jerks!

15
00:04:44,691 --> 00:04:46,044
I'll screw you!

16
00:04:47,411 --> 00:04:48,480
I'll screw you!

17
00:05:06,211 --> 00:05:08,008
Have you seen Ermanno?

18
00:06:01,771 --> 00:06:05,081
- I'll screw you! Now!
- Get lost!

19
00:06:41,091 --> 00:06:42,280
What the hell are you doing?

20
00:07:15,011 --> 00:07:16,763
My phone's been stolen!

21
00:08:00,811 --> 00:08:02,881
I'm starring in two TV dramas...

22
00:08:03,091 --> 00:08:05,047
I'm playing a Pope in one,

23
00:08:05,211 --> 00:08:08,283
and a junkie on the road to recovery
in the other.

24
00:08:08,411 --> 00:08:12,120
Impressive!
No theatre work?

25
00:08:12,251 --> 00:08:15,323
I'm supposed to do
Shakespeare with Pietro, but...

26
00:08:15,531 --> 00:08:17,487
it has to be at least
three hours long,

27
00:08:17,651 --> 00:08:22,281
be an ambitious project,
and no more small cities!

28
00:08:22,611 --> 00:08:26,445
I'm trying to write a piece
for theatre, and the concept is...

29
00:08:26,571 --> 00:08:30,530
- What about you?
- I might give up acting.

30
00:08:30,691 --> 00:08:33,922
In this shitty country there are
never any good female roles.

31
00:08:34,091 --> 00:08:37,049
I'll write my first novel,
a Proust-style piece.

32
00:08:37,171 --> 00:08:39,844
Really?
Proust is my favorite writer!

33
00:08:39,971 --> 00:08:42,087
Along with Ammaniti...

34
00:08:43,011 --> 00:08:44,490
What a coincidence.

35
00:08:52,171 --> 00:08:53,604
Who is that woman?

36
00:08:53,771 --> 00:08:55,807
Don't you recognize her?
It's Lorena.

37
00:08:56,131 --> 00:08:57,325
Who?

38
00:08:57,451 --> 00:09:01,524
An ex TV showgirl, now in
full physical and mental decline.

39
00:09:01,651 --> 00:09:05,690
Never seen her! But then
I've never had a television.

40
00:09:05,811 --> 00:09:10,282
Viola, I know you don't have one.
You tell me all the time.

41
00:09:10,451 --> 00:09:13,090
- What does she do now?
- Nothing, of course.

42
00:09:15,051 --> 00:09:16,564
Happy birthday, Jep!

43
00:09:16,731 --> 00:09:18,881
Happy birthday, Rome!

44
00:10:02,891 --> 00:10:05,610
La Colita!

45
00:11:24,771 --> 00:11:27,968
To this question, as kids,

46
00:11:28,091 --> 00:11:31,447
my friends always gave
the same answer...

47
00:11:31,931 --> 00:11:33,683
"pussy".

48
00:11:34,211 --> 00:11:35,929
Whereas I answered...

49
00:11:36,531 --> 00:11:38,840
"the smell of old
people's houses".

50
00:11:39,571 --> 00:11:41,243
The question was:

51
00:11:41,371 --> 00:11:45,922
"What do you like most, really,
in life?"

52
00:11:46,931 --> 00:11:50,082
I was destined for sensibility.

53
00:11:50,731 --> 00:11:54,246
I was destined to become a writer.

54
00:11:54,691 --> 00:11:59,606
I was destined to become
Jep Gambardella.

55
00:12:09,211 --> 00:12:11,327
You paid no attention
to me tonight!

56
00:12:11,531 --> 00:12:15,080
Romano, don't start moaning,
we're not an item.

57
00:12:15,651 --> 00:12:18,245
- You liked that guy?
- I like everyone and no one.

58
00:12:18,371 --> 00:12:21,249
But I wonder why you're always
with me when it's no one's turn.

59
00:12:21,371 --> 00:12:25,046
- Will you take me to the airport?
- Sure. What time are you leaving?

60
00:12:26,531 --> 00:12:28,328
- In three hours.
- Three hours?

61
00:12:29,931 --> 00:12:32,604
Then I should crash on your sofa...

62
00:12:32,731 --> 00:12:36,963
Go home, I need to pack
and I don't want anyone around.

63
00:12:37,091 --> 00:12:40,003
- But I live miles away.
- See you at 8:00.

64
00:12:47,171 --> 00:12:49,002
Goodnight.

65
00:13:02,131 --> 00:13:04,008
Guys?

66
00:13:20,571 --> 00:13:22,448
Guys?

67
00:13:38,531 --> 00:13:40,044
Children!

68
00:14:07,731 --> 00:14:09,244
Run along!

69
00:15:07,051 --> 00:15:08,723
Catellani?

70
00:15:10,771 --> 00:15:12,250
The best, of course.

71
00:15:14,571 --> 00:15:17,927
Did Catellani the tailor
make your suit?

72
00:16:07,771 --> 00:16:10,649
There was no doubt
about Malagna's shady intentions.

73
00:16:10,771 --> 00:16:15,242
The girl should be rescued
at any cost, without loss of time.

74
00:16:15,971 --> 00:16:17,404
Sir, you drank!

75
00:16:17,531 --> 00:16:19,647
Just enough to forget
my birthday.

76
00:16:20,291 --> 00:16:22,566
- You want infusion?
- Heavens, no!

77
00:16:25,091 --> 00:16:26,683
- I got you a present.
- How sweet!

78
00:16:26,811 --> 00:16:29,530
This is a lucky charm
from my country.

79
00:16:32,011 --> 00:16:35,208
Good thing it's lucky,
because it's pretty ugly.

80
00:16:35,331 --> 00:16:38,050
Keep it on your bedside
and stop complaining!

81
00:16:38,251 --> 00:16:41,926
I will! And thanks.
Wake me up at 15:00, you rascal.

82
00:16:42,891 --> 00:16:44,802
You're funny when you call me that!

83
00:20:01,011 --> 00:20:03,206
I don't love you!

84
00:20:06,891 --> 00:20:08,609
Brilliant!

85
00:20:17,531 --> 00:20:19,125
Did you enjoy the performance?

86
00:20:21,651 --> 00:20:23,369
Parts of it.

87
00:20:23,491 --> 00:20:26,005
That violent head-butt
made me understand many things.

88
00:20:26,131 --> 00:20:28,087
- Let's start from the beginning.
- Or the end?

89
00:20:28,771 --> 00:20:30,966
You know, Talia Concept
loves to provoke.

90
00:20:31,131 --> 00:20:34,601
Don't bother, there are more
important things than provoking me.

91
00:20:34,771 --> 00:20:38,446
And this habit of speaking
in the third person is unbearable.

92
00:20:38,611 --> 00:20:39,964
What are you reading?

93
00:20:40,131 --> 00:20:43,487
I don't need to read, I live
on vibrations, extrasensory ones.

94
00:20:43,611 --> 00:20:49,561
Extra-sensoriality aside,
what do you mean by vibrations?

95
00:20:49,731 --> 00:20:52,086
The poetry of vibrations cannot
be described

96
00:20:52,211 --> 00:20:54,850
with the vulgarity of words.

97
00:20:55,531 --> 00:20:57,647
Well, try at least.

98
00:20:57,811 --> 00:20:59,767
I'm an artist,
I don't need to explain jack shit.

99
00:20:59,971 --> 00:21:04,487
So I'll write: "Lives on vibrations,
but she doesn't know what they are."

100
00:21:04,731 --> 00:21:06,767
I'm starting to dislike
this interview,

101
00:21:06,891 --> 00:21:08,802
I sense conflictuality in you.

102
00:21:08,971 --> 00:21:12,247
- Conflictuality as a vibration?
- As a pain in the ass.

103
00:21:12,411 --> 00:21:15,084
Let's talk about my mom's
abusive boyfriend.

104
00:21:15,291 --> 00:21:18,761
No! I want to know
what a vibration is.

105
00:21:21,931 --> 00:21:24,240
It's my radar to intercept
the world.

106
00:21:24,411 --> 00:21:26,402
Your radar... meaning?

107
00:21:27,451 --> 00:21:29,442
You're a pain in the ass.

108
00:21:29,571 --> 00:21:31,527
We got off to a bad start...

109
00:21:31,651 --> 00:21:34,404
Talia Concept wants to be
interviewed by your paper,

110
00:21:34,531 --> 00:21:37,364
it has many readers.
But you're biased.

111
00:21:37,491 --> 00:21:41,200
Write about how she has sex
with her fiance 11 times a day,

112
00:21:41,331 --> 00:21:43,128
he's a talented conceptual artist,

113
00:21:43,251 --> 00:21:46,288
he covers basketballs with confetti!
He's sensational!

114
00:21:46,411 --> 00:21:49,608
Talia Concept is talking about
things that are meaningless to me.

115
00:21:49,731 --> 00:21:52,086
All I've heard
is unpublishable fluff.

116
00:21:52,251 --> 00:21:54,606
You can't charm me
with things like:

117
00:21:54,731 --> 00:21:57,484
"I'm an artist,
I don't need to explain".

118
00:21:57,611 --> 00:22:00,079
Our paper has a core
of cultured readers

119
00:22:00,251 --> 00:22:02,719
that don't want to be taken
for fools. I work for that core.

120
00:22:02,851 --> 00:22:05,411
So let me talk about my eventful,

121
00:22:05,571 --> 00:22:08,244
difficult but necessary
journey as an artist!

122
00:22:08,371 --> 00:22:10,009
Necessary for who?

123
00:22:10,131 --> 00:22:13,282
For heaven's sake, madam,
what is a vibration?

124
00:22:15,211 --> 00:22:18,009
- I don't know.
- You don't know.

125
00:22:18,171 --> 00:22:20,526
You are an obsessive jerk!

126
00:22:20,651 --> 00:22:24,360
I'll tell your editor to send me
a journalist of a higher stature.

127
00:22:24,491 --> 00:22:27,608
A piece of advice:
When you speak to my editor,

128
00:22:27,771 --> 00:22:31,400
go easy on the stature business.
She's a dwarf, you know.

129
00:22:33,051 --> 00:22:35,770
Jep, this interview is a hoot!

130
00:22:35,931 --> 00:22:37,967
Maybe, but don't send me

131
00:22:38,091 --> 00:22:40,143
to interview someone
who head-butts walls again.

132
00:22:40,971 --> 00:22:43,883
- You know what the trick is?
- Foam rubber.

133
00:22:44,051 --> 00:22:45,609
Amateur dramatics isn't dead.

134
00:22:45,771 --> 00:22:49,844
Did you get offended
about the stature comment?

135
00:22:50,011 --> 00:22:53,481
Don't be silly!
That's the funniest bit!

136
00:22:53,651 --> 00:22:55,801
I'm a dwarf, it's no secret.

137
00:22:55,971 --> 00:22:58,849
It's the first and last thing
everyone says about me.

138
00:22:59,011 --> 00:23:02,367
You're a spectacular woman, Dadina.
You've had the career you deserve.

139
00:23:02,531 --> 00:23:05,887
But you haven't had the career
you deserve.

140
00:23:06,491 --> 00:23:08,482
Maybe I don't have much to say...

141
00:23:08,611 --> 00:23:12,206
Bullshit, you're lazy.
You never leave Rome.

142
00:23:12,371 --> 00:23:14,931
Go to Giglio to do that report
on the Concordia

143
00:23:15,051 --> 00:23:16,769
I've asked you to do 50 times.

144
00:23:21,171 --> 00:23:24,481
Re-heated rice is always tastier
than freshly cooked rice.

145
00:23:24,651 --> 00:23:26,960
The old is better than the new.

146
00:23:27,771 --> 00:23:29,523
Plans tonight, cherie?

147
00:23:29,691 --> 00:23:33,240
As the great De Blasi,
my predecessor, said:

148
00:23:33,411 --> 00:23:37,086
"Tonight I'll do two things,
eat soup and have a shag."

149
00:23:37,251 --> 00:23:39,560
Two things that contradict
each other.

150
00:23:39,731 --> 00:23:42,689
That's what I'd say too,
and she'd reply, in a serious tone:

151
00:23:42,851 --> 00:23:46,969
"No, Dadina, they don't,
because they're both hot."

152
00:23:49,251 --> 00:23:52,482
There's a publishing house
in Ancona, it's not that small,

153
00:23:52,691 --> 00:23:54,647
they want an interview book
about you.

154
00:23:54,771 --> 00:23:58,650
Another interview book?
We're obsessed with interviews!

155
00:23:58,771 --> 00:24:01,888
Can't you hear them?
"As I always say"...to who?

156
00:24:02,051 --> 00:24:03,450
Forget it!

157
00:24:03,571 --> 00:24:06,165
And honestly,
who'll buy a book called:

158
00:24:06,291 --> 00:24:09,363
"Visions and revisions.
Jep Gambardella's Galaxy"?

159
00:24:09,531 --> 00:24:11,283
It's a serious title!

160
00:24:11,451 --> 00:24:14,170
Unfortunately in this country,
in order to be taken seriously,

161
00:24:14,331 --> 00:24:16,401
you have to take yourself seriously.

162
00:24:16,571 --> 00:24:20,883
I only wrote one novel, 40 years ago.
Impossible to find too...

163
00:24:21,051 --> 00:24:23,884
Bullshit, "The Human Apparatus"
was a masterpiece!

164
00:24:24,051 --> 00:24:25,962
It even won the... what was it?

165
00:24:26,131 --> 00:24:28,691
- The Bancarella Prize.
- Shit, the Bancarella Prize!

166
00:24:28,851 --> 00:24:32,161
You're very kind, but forget it...
it'd be too pompous.

167
00:24:32,291 --> 00:24:35,681
I can't, you'll put me
in an awkward position.

168
00:24:35,891 --> 00:24:38,963
I've agreed and I've even accepted
an advance...

169
00:24:39,091 --> 00:24:40,524
- How much?
- 1,500 Euros.

170
00:24:40,731 --> 00:24:43,165
Give it back,
I'll give you 1,500 Euros.

171
00:24:43,331 --> 00:24:46,482
By the way,
I spoke to the theatre people.

172
00:24:46,611 --> 00:24:49,683
They'll give you three nights
but you pay for the lights.

173
00:24:49,851 --> 00:24:51,603
Who cares about that!

174
00:24:51,771 --> 00:24:53,727
Jep, this is great news.

175
00:24:54,131 --> 00:24:56,804
It's really great news.
Thank you!

176
00:25:02,731 --> 00:25:06,360
Are you still up?
It's time to go to bed.

177
00:25:06,531 --> 00:25:08,522
That's Viola Bartoli,
Bartoli's widow.

178
00:25:08,651 --> 00:25:11,211
The guy who was killed,
the actual Bartoli.

179
00:25:11,411 --> 00:25:15,484
Viola has a 50 meter yacht
that belonged to Himmler, the Nazi.

180
00:25:15,771 --> 00:25:17,727
You know what I call Viola?

181
00:25:17,891 --> 00:25:20,405
- No, what?
- "To-good-to-poo".

182
00:25:20,571 --> 00:25:24,041
- I don't understand.
- Because she's pernickety.

183
00:25:24,171 --> 00:25:26,480
Usually pernickety people don't poo.

184
00:25:26,651 --> 00:25:29,688
When I introduced Trumeau
to my family, my father said:

185
00:25:29,811 --> 00:25:33,281
"Miss, before marrying my son,
have you ever seen him poo?"

186
00:25:33,491 --> 00:25:35,766
- How gross!
- It's not as bad as you think.

187
00:25:35,931 --> 00:25:40,402
Actually, my wife and I are the only
couple in Italy who are in love.

188
00:25:40,531 --> 00:25:42,487
Orietta, watch out for Lello.

189
00:25:42,651 --> 00:25:44,209
Yes, I know.

190
00:25:44,331 --> 00:25:47,129
He's the world's greatest salesman,
he cons everyone.

191
00:25:47,251 --> 00:25:49,128
In no time he'll get you to spend
every penny

192
00:25:49,251 --> 00:25:50,366
on whatever he's selling.

193
00:25:50,531 --> 00:25:51,805
You always flatter me.

194
00:25:51,971 --> 00:25:55,600
Just because I express myself well
doesn't mean I'm always working!

195
00:25:55,731 --> 00:25:57,722
- What do you do?
- I sell toys.

196
00:25:57,891 --> 00:25:59,722
Not just in a shop,

197
00:25:59,891 --> 00:26:03,247
he's a wholesaler on a global scale,
he even sells to the Chinese!

198
00:26:03,371 --> 00:26:04,599
What about him?

199
00:26:04,771 --> 00:26:08,889
Don't you know him? Sebastiano Paf,
perhaps Italy's greatest poet.

200
00:26:09,051 --> 00:26:14,364
He wrote: "Up with life,
down with reminiscence."

201
00:26:15,291 --> 00:26:18,044
He's on the Dukan Diet,
so Dadina won't leave him.

202
00:26:18,371 --> 00:26:19,201
Is he with her?

203
00:26:19,331 --> 00:26:22,050
- He is, but she...
- Like at high school.

204
00:26:23,131 --> 00:26:24,928
Why doesn't he ever talk?

205
00:26:25,091 --> 00:26:27,047
Because he listens.

206
00:26:29,051 --> 00:26:32,168
- Stop sniffing up with your nose?
- Bugger off.

207
00:26:32,291 --> 00:26:36,682
Jep's found a theatre for me.
Do you want the lead role?

208
00:26:36,851 --> 00:26:39,729
I'm no longer an actress,
I'm a writer now.

209
00:26:39,971 --> 00:26:41,723
Maybe...

210
00:26:42,531 --> 00:26:44,442
Maybe I'll direct a film.

211
00:26:44,611 --> 00:26:48,524
- Viola, darling!
- Help me, I'm worried about my son.

212
00:26:48,691 --> 00:26:51,603
- What can I do?
- Why don't you talk to him?

213
00:26:51,731 --> 00:26:54,120
You always say you're good
with strangers...

214
00:26:54,251 --> 00:26:56,207
That's the problem, I'm too good.

215
00:26:56,371 --> 00:27:00,603
- Is he seeing a therapist?
- Yes, but he wants to stop going.

216
00:27:00,771 --> 00:27:05,208
Take him to a psychiatrist, they're
pragmatic: Ativan, Prozac and so on.

217
00:27:05,371 --> 00:27:07,123
That stuff makes him feel worse.

218
00:27:07,291 --> 00:27:10,840
Relax, he's always been odd,
he is what he is.

219
00:27:10,971 --> 00:27:14,043
By the way, have you tried
this rascal's endive quiche?

220
00:27:14,211 --> 00:27:17,681
It's the first time she's made it
and it's better than my mom's,

221
00:27:17,851 --> 00:27:21,161
please, you must try some!

222
00:27:26,571 --> 00:27:28,368
You changed your hair color.

223
00:27:29,691 --> 00:27:32,364
I feel Pirandelloesque lately...

224
00:27:33,891 --> 00:27:36,724
- Great jazz, no?
- Not really.

225
00:27:36,851 --> 00:27:41,322
The Ethiopian jazz scene is the only
interesting one today.

226
00:27:41,491 --> 00:27:44,688
I'm from Milan, to be honest...
I find Romans...

227
00:27:45,211 --> 00:27:46,360
unbearable!

228
00:27:46,531 --> 00:27:49,170
The best people in Rome
are the tourists.

229
00:27:49,291 --> 00:27:50,690
Take Italy...

230
00:27:50,851 --> 00:27:54,127
What are we famous for overseas?
Fashion and pizza.

231
00:27:54,291 --> 00:27:56,680
A country of weavers and grocers.

232
00:27:56,851 --> 00:28:00,730
How can someone who sells toys,
bringing joy to the world,

233
00:28:00,851 --> 00:28:03,968
be such a pessimist
and a defeatist? You're dark.

234
00:28:04,131 --> 00:28:05,689
- Dark?
- Yes.

235
00:28:05,851 --> 00:28:08,570
I heard Gisella Montanelli
went to loan sharks

236
00:28:08,731 --> 00:28:10,403
to pay her hairdressing debts.

237
00:28:10,571 --> 00:28:12,163
Jep says I'm dark!

238
00:28:12,331 --> 00:28:13,844
Gisella's really sunk that low?

239
00:28:13,971 --> 00:28:18,999
Rome is the only city in the world
where Marxism has truly existed.

240
00:28:19,171 --> 00:28:22,049
You can't excel over others
for more than a week,

241
